# This file tells git which files and folders to ignore in your project.
# It's a best practice for keeping your repository clean from build artifacts,
# user-specific files, and sensitive data.

## User-specific files
# These files are generated by IDEs like Visual Studio and are unique to each developer's machine.
.vs/
*.suo
*.user
*.userosscache
*.sln.docstates

## Build artifacts
# These folders contain the compiled output of your project. They can be rebuilt from source at any time.
[Bb]in/
[Oo]bj/
[Tt]est[Rr]esult*/

## NuGet packages
# Ignore the packages folder for old-style .NET projects. For modern .NET, packages are managed globally.
packages/
*.nupkg
*.snupkg
# Don't ignore the NuGet packages directory in the root of the solution.
!/packages/

## Runtime files
# Log files, local databases, and other temporary files generated during execution.
*.log
*.tlog
*.dll.log
*.sqlite
*.sqlite-journal

## Secrets and sensitive configuration 🛡️
# NEVER commit secrets, API keys, or connection strings. Use user secrets or environment variables.
secrets.json
*.env

## OS-specific files
# Files generated by the operating system.
# Windows
Thumbs.db
# macOS
.DS_Store